-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Afribank, Equity Bank, KenolKobil and Oceanic
-- Eric Ombok
-- 2010-07-20T12:49:08Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-20/sub-saharan-african-equities-afribank-equity-bank-kenolkobil-oceanic.html

          
          
             Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  snapped two
days of declines, rising 0.4 percent to close at 1,693.29 as of
1:30 p.m. in Port Louis.  
 Kenya’s  All-Share Index  gained 0.6 percent to close at 76.1
as of 2:05 p.m. in Nairobi. The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index  rose 0.2 percent to 24,816.83, while Namibia’s
 FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  dropped for a fifth day, falling 0.6
percent to 750.79 as of 1:30 p.m. in Windhoek. The  Ghana Stock
Exchange All-Share Index  retreated 0.5 percent to 6,259.3 as of
12:30 p.m. in Accra.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 Afribank Plc  (AFRIBANK NL), a Nigerian lender bailed out by
the central bank last year, increased 9 kobo, or the maximum
daily limit of 5 percent, to 1.89 naira, the strongest price
since July 8.  Intercontinental Bank Plc  (INTERCON NL) gained 8
kobo, or 4.7 percent, to 1.79 naira, while  Oceanic Bank Plc 
(OCEANIC NL) climbed 8 kobo, or 4.9 percent, to 1.7 naira.
President Goodluck Jonathan signed into law a bill creating a
company known as the Asset Management Corp. of Nigeria, or
Amcon, that will buy bad debts from the lenders.  
 Equity Bank Ltd.  (EQBNK KN), Kenya’s biggest lender by
customers, climbed for a fourth day, rising 25 cents, or 1.1
percent, to 24 shillings, the highest level this month. Profit
for the first fiscal half through June grew 44 percent to 3.01
billion shillings ($36.8 million).  
 KenolKobil Ltd.  (KNOC KN), a Kenyan fuel retailer, fell the
most this month, dropping 30 cents, or 2.87 percent, to 10.3
shillings. Kenya Petroleum Refineries Ltd. is holding more than
4 billion shillings ($49 million) of refined fuel belonging to
KenolKobil.  
